CASE STUDY: UPI Online Payment Fraud

Online UPI fraud is a cybercrime where fraudsters trick people during digital payments and take money from their bank account without permission. It has become common because many people use UPI daily but still dont know all safety rules.

A typical fraud starts when a person receives a call or message from someone pretending to be a buyer customer care agent or bank worker. The fraudster says money will be sent and asks the victim to scan a QR code or click a payment link. The victim thinks this is needed for receiving money. After scanning the QR code the app asks for UPI pin. When the victim enters the pin the money actually gets deducted from the account instead of being received.

In many cases students small shop owners and elderly people are targeted because they trust quickly and may not understand how UPI works fully. Fraudsters often speak politely and create urgency so the victim acts fast without checking.

A realistic example is of a student who was selling books online. A fake buyer agreed to pay immediately and sent a QR code saying scan this to get payment. The student scanned it and entered the pin two times because first transaction showed failed. Within one minute 8000 rupees was gone from the bank account and the buyer number became unreachable.
